title: Add lastDataPublishTime in hive table/partition properties
body:
### Changes
- Added `lastDataPublishTime` property in hive table properties and partition properties.
- This property store the time when new data was published into a partition or a table.
- Currently there is no way to know when new data gets added to an existing partition, this property will allow applications to use as a watermark to process new data for a partition.
- It provides a guarantee that no new data has been added since this time as the timestamp used is greater than the actual publish time which happens in the task publisher.

title: Parallelize commit rebased
body:
Guide to this PR:
- Created a class `SafeDatasetCommit`. Refactored a lot of the commit logic from `JobContext` to this class.
- `JobContext` creates an `IteratorExecutor` to execute dataset commits in parallel.
- Added a `isThreadSafe` method to `DataPublisher`. If this is false (default), Gobblin will automatically fall back to serial commit even if user choses parallel commit.
- Added a unit test to ensure `JobContext` handles publisher failure semantics correctly.

ing fileset.

title: Integration with Confluent Schema Registry, Confluent Deserializers, and Kafka Deserializers
body:
- Adding integration with Confluent's Schema Registry - https://github.com/confluentinc/schema-registry
  - `ConfluentKafkaSchemaRegistry.java`
- Created `KafkaDeserializerExtractor` which wraps Kafka's `Deserializer` API
  - Kafka's `Deserializer` interface provides a generic way for converting `byte[]` to Java Objects
  - The `KafkaDeserializerExtractor` takes in a path to a fully qualified implementation of `Deserializer` and uses it to convert they `byte[]` into a Java Object
  - It has built in support for a few known `Deserializer`s including Confluents `KafkaAvroDeserializer` and `KafkaJsonDeserializer`
- Created a `KafkaGsonDeserializer` that converts `byte[]` to `JsonElement`s
- Updated the `gobblin-docs/case-studies/Kafka-HDFS-Ingestion.md` to document all of these new features
- Unit tests added

title: Initial commit for gobblin-cluster; gobblin-yarn refactoring
body:
Initial commit for a new sub-module called `gobblin-cluster`
- `gobblin-cluster` provides clustering abilities independent of `gobblin-yarn`
- `gobblin-cluster` essentially just uses Helix for its clustering abilities, and leaves the task of resource management to an external system (e.g. YARN, Mesos, or a CLI)
- This PR is just a refactoring of `gobblin-yarn`, there is no new additional logic, only refactoring
- `gobblin-yarn` already has all the integration with Helix necessary for an initial version of `gobblin-cluster` to work
- More features can be added on top of this, but all the required code to get a basic Gobblin Cluster up and running is now present in `gobblin-cluster`
- This PR basically takes all the Helix logic in `gobblin-yarn` and puts it into `gobblin-cluster`; `gobblin-cluster` has no YARN dependencies
- Most classes have simply been renamed, and their package name changes; but there are few classes that were split into multiple classes:
  - A portion of `GobblinYarnConfigurationKeys` was split into `GobblinClusterConfigurationKeys`
  - Most of the logic in `GobblinApplicationMaster` was moved into `GobblinClusterManager`
    - `GobblinApplicationMaster` now only runs the YARN specific services:
      - `YarnService`
      - `YarnContainerSecurityManager`
      - `GobblinYarnLogSource`
    - `GobblinApplicationMaster` now `extends` `GobblinClusterManager`
  - A portion of `GobblinYarnMetricTagNames` was split into `GobblinClusterMetricTagNames`
  - A portion of `YarnHelixUtils` was split into `GobblinClusterUtils`
  - A portion of `gobblin.yarn.HelixMessageSubTypes` was split into `gobblin.cluster.HelixMessageSubTypes`
  - Most of the logic in `GobblinWorkUnitRunner` was moved into `GobblinTaskRunner`
    - `GobblinWorkUnitRunner` was renamed to `GobblinYarnTaskRunner`
    - `GobblinYarnTaskRunner` now extends `GobblinTaskRunner`

Tests:
- `GobblinApplicationMasterTest` was moved into `gobblin-cluster`
  - It was renamed to `GobblinClusterManagerTest`
- `GobblinHelixJobLauncherTest` was moved into `gobblin-cluster`
- `GobblinHelixTaskTest` was moved into `gobblin-cluster`
- `GobblinWorkUnitRunnerTest` was moved into `gobblin-cluster`
  - It was renamed to `GobblinTaskRunnerTest`
- `JobConfigurationManagerTest` was moved into `gobblin-cluster`

All other changes are simply re-factoring of logic to accommodate the above changes.
- Other changes:
  - Added the `Alpha` tag to all classes in `gobblin-cluster`
  - Added `CLUSTER` to the enum `JobLauncherType` in `JobExecutionInfo.pdsc`

While this PR provides the basis for running Gobblin independent from any resource manager, there are certain features that are still missing:
- Launch scripts for `GobblinClusterManager` and `GobblinTaskRunner`
- A solid log aggregation story; `gobblin-yarn` has `GobblinYarnLogSource` but this class depends on the existence of a distributed file system to do log aggregation
- A global application id - `gobblin-yarn` derives its application id from the application master id, but `gobblin-cluster` has no such concept; currently the application is hardcoded to `1`

title: Modify QueryBasedSource to allow pulling multiple tables in the same job
body:
This PR modifies `QueryBasedSource` so that it is possible to specify multiple table names in the same job.

Previously a job can only specify a single table name via `source.entity` or `extract.table.name`. Now two new properties are added: `source.entities` and `extract.table.names`.

Related changes:
- Moved the method to obtain topic-specific properties from `KafkaSource` to `DatasetUtils` so that it can be used by `QueryBasedSource` as well.
- Removed the usage of the deprecated watermark methods in `QueryBasedSource` and `QueryBasedExtractor`, and replaced them with the new JSON-based `Watermark`.
- Use a simple round robin method in `QueryBasedSource` to pack `WorkUnit`s into `MultiWorkUnit`s. More sophisticated bin packing methods can be added later if there's a need to do so.

title: Unified way to execute Hive and MR-based compaction jobs
body:
Currently the execution of the Hive and MR-based compactors is not out of the box, needs extra work:
- there's no implementation for MR compaction for CLI execution
- Hive compactor is a standalone package that needs to be built separately

This PR tries to fix these issues. A new shell script **bin/gobblin-compaction.sh** was added with which one can execute both Hive and MR-based compaction jobs from the CLI.

```
Usage: gobblin-compaction.sh [OPTION] --type <compaction type: hive or mr> --conf <compaction configuration file>
Where OPTION can be:
  --projectversion <version>    Gobblin version to be used. If set, overrides the distribution build version
  --logdir <log dir>            Gobblin's log directory: if not set, taken from ${GOBBLIN_LOG_DIR} if present. 
  --help                        Display this help and exit
```

I assumed that the executable gobblin-compaction.jar and tarball creation are no longer needed.
